ResNet‑50 (2015) – The Classic Deep CNN That Changed Everything
ResNet‑50 is one of the most influential CNN architectures ever created.
It introduced residual connections, which solved the “vanishing gradient” problem and allowed networks to go much deeper without losing accuracy.
Even today, ResNet‑50 remains a strong, reliable baseline for image classification and transfer learning.

How It Works (Simple Version)
Image → Convolution Layers → Residual Blocks → Global Pooling → Classifier → Output
The key innovation is the skip connection, which lets the model “skip” layers and learn residuals instead of full transformations.


The Key Insight
Before ResNet, deeper networks often performed worse because gradients vanished as they flowed backward.
ResNet solves this by adding:
Residual Connections
Instead of learning: 𝐻(𝑥)
the network learns: 𝐹(𝑥)=𝐻(𝑥)−𝑥
and outputs: 𝐻(𝑥)=𝐹(𝑥)+𝑥
This simple idea:
stabilizes training
allows very deep networks (50, 101, 152 layers)
improves accuracy
reduces overfitting
ResNet‑50 is the 50‑layer version using bottleneck residual blocks.

Why It's Good for Your Waste Project
Benefit		                Explanation
Reliable & well‑understood	One of the most widely used CNNs in research and industry
Strong transfer learning	Pretrained on ImageNet with excellent generalization
Good at textures & shapes	Ideal for waste images with varied materials
Stable training	            Residual connections prevent gradient issues
Lightweight	                ~25.6M parameters — smaller than many modern models

Simple Architecture Diagram:
Input Image
    ↓
[Conv Stem] → Initial convolution + max pooling
    ↓
[Residual Block Stage 1] → 3 bottleneck blocks
    ↓
[Residual Block Stage 2] → 4 bottleneck blocks
    ↓
[Residual Block Stage 3] → 6 bottleneck blocks
    ↓
[Residual Block Stage 4] → 3 bottleneck blocks
    ↓
[Global Average Pooling]
    ↓
[Fully Connected Classifier]
    ↓
Output

Why Transfer Learning
ResNet‑50 pretrained on ImageNet learns:
edges
textures
shapes
object parts

These features transfer extremely well to your waste dataset, especially for:
plastics
metals
paper textures
glass reflections

Why Two-Phase Training
Phase	    What	                                    Why
Phase 1	    Freeze backbone, train classifier	        Quickly adapts to waste classes without disturbing pretrained features
Phase 2	    Unfreeze backbone, fine‑tune entire model	Allows deeper layers to specialize to waste-specific textures

Training Strategy

Hyperparameter Selection
Hyperparameter	        Value	        Justification
Batch size	            32	            Works well with ResNet‑50’s memory footprint
LR (Phase 1)	        1e‑3	        Classifier head is randomly initialized
LR (Phase 2)	        1e‑5	        Prevents over‑updating deep residual layers
Optimizer	            AdamW or SGD	Both work; AdamW converges faster
Epochs (Phase 1)	    15–20	        Enough for classifier convergence
Epochs (Phase 2)	    30–40	        Allows stable fine‑tuning
ResNet‑50 is less sensitive than ConvNeXt v2, but benefits from similar LR scheduling.

Addressing Class Imbalance
The 52:1 imbalance is a critical challenge. We address it through:
Method	        How It Helps
Weighted loss	Forces attention to rare classes
Oversampling	Ensures minority classes appear frequently
Augmentation	Prevents overfitting on rare classes

Loss Function
Use weighted cross‑entropy, where: weight𝑖 = 1/frequency𝑖
This helps ResNet‑50 learn rare classes like bottle-oil-full.

