ConvNeXt (2022) – A Modernized CNN That Competes With Transformers
ConvNeXt is a pure CNN architecture redesigned using insights from Vision Transformers (ViT).
It keeps the efficiency and inductive biases of CNNs, but updates the architecture with modern design choices that make it competitive with transformer models.

How It Works (Simple Version)
Image → Modern CNN blocks (ConvNeXt Blocks) → Global feature extraction → Classifier → Output

ConvNeXt keeps the classic CNN idea (local receptive fields) but modernizes it with:
Larger kernels (7×7 depthwise convs)
LayerNorm instead of BatchNorm
Inverted bottlenecks (like MobileNetV2)
GELU activations (like Transformers)
Simplified, scalable architecture

The Key Insight
ConvNeXt asks:
'What if we take a ResNet and upgrade it using all the good ideas from Transformers?'
So it incorporates:
Patchify stem (like ViT)
Depthwise convolutions (lightweight, efficient)
LayerNorm everywhere (Transformer-style normalization)
Large kernels (to capture global context without attention)
Simplified block design (fewer components, more efficient)
This gives you a model that:
behaves like a CNN
performs like a transformer
trains efficiently
runs fast on GPUs and edge devices

Why It's Good for Your Waste Project
Benefit		                Explanation
High accuracy	            ConvNeXt-Tiny reaches ~82–84% ImageNet accuracy, competitive with ViT
Efficient	                Depthwise convs + simplified blocks = fast inference
Stable training	            LayerNorm + GELU + modern design improves convergence
Great for transfer learning	Pretrained weights capture strong texture + shape features
Robust to small datasets	CNN inductive biases help when data is limited or imbalanced

Simple Architecture Diagram:
Input Image
    ↓
[Patchify Stem] → Converts image into non-overlapping patches
    ↓
[ConvNeXt Stages] → Large-kernel depthwise convs + LayerNorm + MLP-like blocks
    ↓
[Global Average Pooling]
    ↓
[Classifier Head]
    ↓
Output


Why Transfer Learning
ConvNeXt pretrained on ImageNet learns:
edges
textures
shapes
object parts
Even though ImageNet doesn’t contain waste categories, these features transfer extremely well to your domain.

Why Two-Phase Training
Phase	    What	                                    Why
Phase 1	    Freeze backbone, train classifier	        Quickly adapt to waste classes without disturbing pretrained features
Phase 2	    Unfreeze backbone, fine‑tune entire model	Gradually specialize ConvNeXt to waste-specific textures and shapes
This avoids catastrophic forgetting and stabilizes training.

Training Strategy

Hyperparameter Selection
Hyperparameter	        Value	    Justification
Batch size	            32	        Good balance of stability and memory usage
LR (Phase 1)	        1e‑3	    Higher LR for training the new classifier head
LR (Phase 2)	        1e‑5	    Lower LR for fine‑tuning the backbone
Optimizer	            AdamW	    Works well with LayerNorm + weight decay
Epochs (Phase 1)	    20	        Enough to adapt classifier
Epochs (Phase 2)	    30–50	    Slow, stable fine‑tuning

Addressing Class Imbalance
The 52:1 imbalance is a critical challenge. We address it through:
Method	        How It Helps
Weighted loss	Rare classes get higher gradient contribution
Oversampling	Ensures minority classes appear frequently
Augmentation	Helps prevent overfitting on rare classes

Loss Function
Use weighted cross‑entropy, where: weight𝑖 = 1/frequency𝑖
This forces ConvNeXt to pay attention to rare classes like bottle-oil-full.

