ConvNeXt v2 (2023) – The Modern CNN Reinvented
ConvNeXt v2 is the successor to ConvNeXt, designed to push CNNs even closer to transformer‑level performance while keeping the efficiency, stability, and inductive biases that make CNNs so effective.
It introduces two major innovations: Global Response Normalization (GRN) and Fully Convolutional Masked Autoencoder (FCMAE) pretraining
Together, these make ConvNeXt v2 one of the strongest CNN families available today.

How It Works (Simple Version)
Image → Patchify Stem → ConvNeXt v2 Blocks (with GRN) → Global Pooling → Classifier → Output
ConvNeXt v2 keeps the modernized CNN design of v1 but improves global feature learning and training stability.

The Key Insight
ConvNeXt v2 asks:
'How do we give CNNs the global awareness and stability of transformers, without using attention?'

It does this through:
1. Global Response Normalization (GRN)
GRN normalizes activations using global statistics, not just local ones.
This helps the model:
understand global context
stabilize gradients
reduce overfitting
improve transfer learning

2. FCMAE Pretraining
A convolutional version of masked autoencoder pretraining.
Benefits:
stronger low‑level feature learning
better generalization
more robust transfer learning
improved performance on small datasets

Why It's Good for Your Waste Project
Benefit		                Explanation
Higher accuracy	            ConvNeXt v2 improves ImageNet accuracy by ~1–2% over v1
Better global understanding	GRN helps capture relationships across the whole image
More stable training	    Especially helpful with imbalanced datasets
Excellent transfer learning	FCMAE pretraining gives stronger features
Efficient	                Still a pure CNN — fast inference, low memory

Simple Architecture Diagram:
Input Image
    ↓
[Patchify Stem] → Converts image into patches (like ViT)
    ↓
[ConvNeXt v2 Blocks] → Large-kernel depthwise convs + GRN + MLP-like layers
    ↓
[Global Average Pooling]
    ↓
[Classifier Head]
    ↓
Output

Why Transfer Learning
ConvNeXt v2 pretrained weights (FCMAE + ImageNet) give you:
strong texture recognition
robust shape understanding
stable gradients
better generalization on small datasets
This is ideal for your waste dataset.

Why Two-Phase Training
Phase	    What	                                    Why
Phase 1	    Freeze backbone, train classifier	        Quickly adapt to waste classes without disturbing pretrained features
Phase 2	    Unfreeze backbone, fine‑tune entire model	GRN + FCMAE features adapt smoothly to your domain

Training Strategy

Hyperparameter Selection
Hyperparameter	        Value	    Justification
Batch size	            32	        Works well with ConvNeXt v2’s depth and normalization
LR (Phase 1)	        1e‑3	    Classifier head is randomly initialized
LR (Phase 2)	        1e‑5	    GRN layers and deep backbone require gentle updates
Optimizer	            AdamW	    Matches original ConvNeXt v2 training setup
Epochs (Phase 1)	    20	        Enough for classifier convergence
Epochs (Phase 2)	    30–50	    Allows stable fine‑tuning of deep layers

Addressing Class Imbalance
The 52:1 imbalance is a critical challenge. We address it through:
Method	        How It Helps
Weighted loss	Forces attention to rare classes
Oversampling	Ensures minority classes appear frequently
Augmentation	Prevents overfitting on rare classes

Loss Function
Use weighted cross‑entropy, where: weight𝑖 = 1/frequency𝑖
This helps ConvNeXt v2 learn rare classes like bottle-oil-full.